SNOW STABILITY 
The avalanche risk has been set at a considerable 2 - 3 out of 5 on the international scale over the last few days. Overnight refreeze of the snowpack has been either non-existant or only very minimal.  Due to this, combined with the recent rain and very warm termperatures, we will continue to see many natural slides of damp heavy snow over the next few days.  These will particularly occur at altitudes between 2400 to 3000 m, especially on N facing slopes which have not yet slid.  A skier could also trigger an avalanche of this type, if on a steep enough gradient. At higher altitudes, above 3000 m, we may see some slab avalanches occurring especially on N facing slopes where the S winds have blown the snow into deep accumulations.  These could occur naturally or be human-triggered.";s:4:"date";s:19:"2013-05-02 12:28:00";s:10:"categories";a:1:{i:0;s:15:"Snow conditions";}s:5:"point";a:2:{i:0;d:45.96962599999999810052031534723937511444091796875;i:1;d:6.59715499999999988034460329799912869930267333984375;}}i:1;a:7:{s:2:"id";i:298;s:5:"title";s:61:"British ski tourer killed by an avalanche on the Grande Casse";s:4:"link";s:49:"http://geoavalanche.org/incident/reports/view/298";s:11:"description";s:812:"A British ski tourer has been killed by an avalanche on the Grande Casse in the Savoie this morning.
